<dl id="n36091f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36091f">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36091f"> 91(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> nod, nod, noddie <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36091f"><li>FW 554.01 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36091f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36091f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36091f">MS BL 47484b-424</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:158 <a name="rBd13" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd13.htm#n36091f">Draft: III&sect;3B.13</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The coach, chariot, and &ldquo;<mark>noddie</mark>&rdquo; could all be hired. The last-named, the predecessor of the &ldquo;Irish jaunting-car&rdquo;, is described by a contemporary as being &ldquo;nothing more than an old cast-off one-horse chaise or chair, with a kind of stool fixed upon the shafts, just before the seat, on which the driver sits.&rdquo; He suggests that the &ldquo;<mark>nod, nod, nodding of the driver</mark>&rdquo; gave its popular name to this conveyance. <font color="green">[Hibernia Curiosa]</font> <small> Samuel A. Ossory Fitzpatrick, <a name="SAOF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SAOF"><cite title="source">Dublin: A Historical and Topographical Account of the City</cite></a> (1907) 201</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n14112d" href="n14all.htm#n14112d">N14 (VI.B.7):112(d)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
